Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also deals with viruses that have already developed drug immunity.
This reality, in some cases, is based on the fact that the combination does not deal as intensively with the current variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
However, the lives of patients can be radically prolonged through a mixture of medicines that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
Moreover, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Republic's Academy of Sciences, the Prague VŠCHT and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to coping with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes affect the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are an assembly of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the resistance problem.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on the protein of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by the atoms of bore, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of HIV virus caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, explaining researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Republic's Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the Scientific Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
