Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General described as the "full image" of the United Nations, Yvo de Boer.
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020 from 25 to 45 per cent compared to 1990 levels, while the main developing countries during the same period would reduce their emissions from 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions from 50 to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched the negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
