Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies aimed at its employees has reminded consumers of the position of companies vis-à-vis the marketing revolution: it is a matter of joining employees to "values" determined from above as they once were, of imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies to conquer markets in the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can result in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilisation seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a prospective vision"; it requires employees to make a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would be to place employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the client.
The full usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – will they encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally comes, after much diversion, to do priority... what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old theory of behaviorist, recently reactivated by the "neurosciences" of the United States and widely disseminated, in their own, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of the commitment of the managers, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr does it comfort the leaders in a mechanical governance position, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize some of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a pre-determined doxa that enables them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and deliver their management of human resources "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
