Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women in younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is what is revealed by the study "Women's fertility and career in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, conducted out of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years, does not leave any doubt: 75% of working mothers have had a limited career because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have unstable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, reject entry into marriage and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed employment have their first child, on average 3.7 years after having settled together. This figure is going to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to achieve it, which has led them to reject the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exerted largely influences maternity, but less the date of common beginning," says CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the age gap of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and their first child is late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who did elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
