Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As this took place with the ABS brake anti-lock system and as it will take place with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure imposed by the European Union is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even though, through its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear-end shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency detected by the system through the driver's footstroke.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to rely on the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
Aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of the so-called emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four cases with injured persons would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device shall exert maximum effort on the brakes to minimize the damage.
